{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Minor risk, easily mitigated -- attribute a standard translation",
    "content": "It is a real but minor risk, and easily mitigated.\n\nThe risk is real because scholars DO notice non-standard renderings of canonical passages -- it is one of the first things a reviewer checks. But the risk is minor because our terms (humaneness, rightness, ritual conduct) are all within the accepted scholarly range. No sinologist would blink at \"humaneness\" for 仁 -- it is Ames and Rosemont's standard rendering and widely used. The departure is not idiosyncratic; it is a legitimate choice.\n\n**Mitigation:** Add a TN at the block quote: \"Translation adapted from D.C. Lau; key terms rendered to maintain consistency with this text's usage.\" This does three things: (1) signals the author knows the standard translations, (2) explains why the rendering differs, (3) gives the reader a cross-reference. The word \"adapted\" is standard practice in philosophical translation -- it tells the reader this is a deliberate choice, not ignorance.\n\nThis is better than using a verbatim standard translation, because verbatim quotation from Lau or Chan would require copyright consideration and would break terminological consistency. \"Adapted from\" is both honest and professional."
  }
}
